[1]
Date: Sat 11 May 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Townsville Bulletin (Queensland, Australia), Fri 10 May 2002 [edited]

Austrlia (Queensland): 4 Confirmed Cases in City of Townsville
--------------------------------------------------------
Public health officials have discovered dengue fever mosquitoes breeding in
23 houses after checks in Railway Estate, West End and Heatley this week.
Director of Environmental Health for Queensland Health John Piispanen said
yesterday that 336 houses had been inspected by Queensland Health and
Townsville City Council environmental health department officers following
4 confirmed cases of dengue fever in the city. "We are aware that 2 of
these cases were imported from Vanuatu where the people had gone for
holidays, but we are very concerned that 2 cases have also been acquired
locally," he said.
Mr Piispanen said there were 17 to 20 different types [?] of the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito responsible for spreading dengue fever. Most were daytime
biters who lurked under tables and bit people on the ankles. He said a
surface spray under furniture and in dark places inside houses would
usually eradicate them. "We want people, especially in these suburbs to be
very vigilant about the issue. We want the people of Townsville and
Thuringowa cities to clean up pot plants, bird baths and even tarpaulins,
in fact anything that can hold water can be a breeding place for these
mosquitoes."
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>
