[3]
Date: Fri 17 May 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source Xinhua News Agency, Wed 15 May 2002 [edited]

Costa Rica: Number of Cases Continues to Rise
---------------------------------------------
Costa Rican Health Minister Maria Del Rocio Saenz warned on Wed 15 May 2002
that an outbreak of dengue fever may hit the country as it did in 1997. She
said a total of 1230 cases of dengue fever has been registered so far this
year, compared with 1928 cases in 2001. The Health Minister said there are
conditions for a possible outbreak of an epidemic like the one in 1997,
when 14 000 cases were registered. In the Central Pacific region alone,
there are 70 000 people who risk infection by the epidemic.
Saenz urged people to eliminate water deposits that could favor the
reproduction of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, the dengue fever vector.
Saenz said the country will soon carry out a fumigation campaign to
eliminate mosquitoes. The dengue season usually peaks in July and August,
when heavy rains provide many places for mosquitoes to lay their eggs.
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>
