[4]
Date: Thu 16 May 2002 2:30 AM
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: La Prensa, Thu 16 May 2002 (Trans. by Mod.MPP) [edited]
<http://www.laprensa.com.ni/nacionales/nacionales-20020516-04.html>

Nicaragua: Decreasing Trend in Last Few Weeks
---------------------------------------------
MINSA [the Ministry of Public Health] announced a preventive plan which
includes house-to-house visits. More people are sick with dengue this
summer than in 2001. According to MINSA statistics, as of the end of Apr
2002 (week 18), 399 cases of classical dengue and 59 cases of dengue
hemorrhagic fever (DHF) have been confirmed, 6 more than last summer.
Nevertheless, Juan Jose Amador, Director of Epidemiology, MINSA, said that
even though in the first months of summer this year there have been more
cases of dengue/DHF than in the same period last year, in the last few
weeks there has been a decreasing trend. During 2001 hundreds were sick
with dengue. The disease reached a historically high level for the country,
and there were 20 deaths due to the disease.
According to MINSA statistics, this year there have only been 2 deaths.
Managua, Chinandega, and Masaya have reported the majority of cases.
Nevertheless, Leon leads the list in terms of the number of reported cases
of DHF, 26, followed by the capital [Managua] with 6 [cases of DHF]. Amador
explained that this time MINSA had organized preventive plans to control
dengue at a cost approaching 2 million cordobas [approx. US $141 143.26; 1
USD = 14.1700 Nicaraguan cordobas on 16 May 2002 exchange market -
Mod.MPP]. He detailed a plan to visit and sanitize 600 000 houses in the
country in 2 months.
At present, MINSA has begun working on disinfestation in Mateare and Ciudad
Sandina. Amador said that almost 100 brigade workers have gone
house-to-house inspecting [for mosquito breeding sites - Mod.MPP] and
explaining to the residents the necessary attention that must be paid to
containers that capture and store water. In addition, the brigades are
conducting mosquito and larvae reduction activities around the households.
Amador said that in 6 weeks they hope to sanitize 240 000 [households] in
the Department of Managua.
[Byline: Amalia Morales]
